The optimization for adsorption of TOR at the B3LYP-D3/6–311++G* level was performed using Gaussian 16 and GaussView [53,54]. Four graphene-based carriers (Fig. 1
                     ), were developed here for the adsorption of the TOR molecule, including pristine graphene (coronene: GG), GG with COOH (COOHGG) and COOHGG with B/N substituted graphene at para positions. Fig. 2
                      displays optimized structures, FMOs and MEP plots of TOR. To confirm the actual minimum in each case, identical-level hessian simulations were run. Results from the DOS were collected using the GaussSum program [55]. The AIM and ELF, LOL, NCI and ESP were done by Multiiwfn [56]. VMD and UCSF Chimerae were used to visualize ESP, NCI iso-surfaces and ELF iso-surfaces [57,58].

By using ΔEb, the stability of TOR-adsorbed complexes was examined. Magnitudes of ΔEb (Table 1
                        ), follow the order BBGG (−55.73 kJmol−1) > COOHGG (−34.63 kJmol−1) > NNGG (–33.84 kJmol−1) > GG (−8.37 kJmol−1) in air while in water, the order is, NNGG (−90.92 kJmol−1) > COOHGG (−89.90 kJmol−1) > BBGG (−67.96 kJmol−1) > GG (−45.03 kJmol−1). The data shows that GG adsorption yields the lowest value and ΔEb between TOR and B/N-doped atoms in parallel position in GG is high (air/water). The thermodynamic parameters are determined and compared to assess the viability of the TOR adsorption on coronene (Table 2
                        ). ΔH for TOR-coronene is negative and is as: COOHGG (−86.97 kJmol−1) > BBGG (−49.75 kJmol−1) > NNGG (−26.39 kJmol−1) > GG (−2.55 kJmol−1) in air and COOHGG (−86.97 kJmol−1) > NNGG (−84.70 kJmol−1) > BBGG (−65.39 kJmol−1) > GG (−40.58 kJmol−1). The fact every ΔS value is negative indicates a spontaneous process. The ΔG is all negative indicating that TOR adsorption happens spontaneously, while the value is less negative for GG. The ΔG values for TOR adsorption are higher for NNGG in air and in COOHGG in water compared to other systems. Negative ΔH is further indication that TOR adsorption on nanocarrier surfaces is exothermic [66].

